{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523635"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:57:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:57:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13913"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13913"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.06,0.05,0.68,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6532"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49067"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6532"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13913"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34098"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"410"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13078"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49067","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49067"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a lesion on her lower lip.  She is unsure if it has changed in size and she stopped using lipstick when she first noticed the lesion. She takes no regular medications. She has had a previous HSV 2 infection which was treated successfully 5 months prior.  She is a retired factory worker. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 1 cm crusted, slightly raised lesion on her lower lip with surrounding erythema (Image) and no other lesions seen on her face. The lesion is firm to touch and non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Herpes simplex infection","Keratoacanthoma","Actinic cheilitis","Squamous cell carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis for this elderly woman with a non-healing lip lesion is \u003Cstrong\u003Esquamous cell carcinoma (SCC)\u003C/strong\u003E. SCCs of the lip typically present as persistent, crusted, or ulcerated lesions that fail to heal. It may occasionally bleed.  They are more common in older individuals with a history of chronic sun exposure in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActinic cheilitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a precancerous condition characterized by dry, scaly lips with loss of the vermillion border. While it can progress to SCC, it typically presents as a more diffuse change on the lower lip rather than a discrete lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal cell carcinoma (BCC)\u003C/strong\u003E can occur on the lips but is less common than SCC in this location. BCCs typically have a pearly, rolled border and may have telangiectasias, which are not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKeratoacanthoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rapidly growing tumor that can resemble SCC. However, it typically presents as a dome-shaped nodule with a central keratin-filled crater, which doesn\u0027t match the description provided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex infection\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents as grouped vesicles on an erythematous base, which evolve into pustules and then crusted lesions. These typically heal within 2-3 weeks, unlike the persistent lesion described in this case.  HSV 2 is also usually causes genital lesions and rarely lesions on the mouth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s age, sun exposure history, and the clinical presentation of a persistent, crusted lesion on the lower lip, squamous cell carcinoma is the most likely diagnosis. Mucosal lesions tend to heal within 2 week thus persisting lesions should always be considered for malignancy.  However, a biopsy would be necessary for definitive diagnosis. Early detection and treatment of lip SCCs are crucial, as they have a higher risk of metastasis compared to SCCs at other cutaneous sites.  A full skin check is warranted to look for other areas of skin damage. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Squamous cell carcinoma of the lip commonly presents as a non-healing ulcer or crusted lesion in elderly individuals with a history of sun exposure.","Biopsy is essential for definitive diagnosis of suspicious lip lesions."],"references":["Wong T, Yap T, Wiesenfeld D. Common benign and malignant oral mucosal disease. Australian Journal of General Practioners. 2020: 49 (9).Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/september/common-benign-and-malignant-oral-mucosal-disease","Oakley A, Tan K, Keefe M, Mitchell G. Kertoacanthoma. In: Dermnet NZ [online]. 2021. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/keratoacanthoma"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34098"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13913"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20850"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20850"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/NgGxXTFikOv5SfDDiV77Re2RPCKZHw.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/NgGxXTFikOv5SfDDiV77Re2RPCKZHw.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34098"},"att